As there are multiple areas in the MS Dynamics instance that require configuration, a step-by-step explanation follows on which configurations need to be made where.

Within the installed apps, you will find the Doxee Document Management App:

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

In the menu of the Doxee Document Management App, you can create queries, configure the iFrame, set process parameters, or define variables.

## 3.1 iFrame Configuration 
3.1.1. General 

In the iFrame configurator, you define which process should be executed, which variables should be passed to the process upon invocation and link the desired query. The iFrame is then linked in the Power Apps, thus representing the integration.

![Ein Bild, das Text, Screenshot, Software, Schrift enthält.  Automatisch generierte Beschreibung](data:image/png;base64,)

- Name: unique name for the iFrame (freely selectable)

- Process name: path to the process to be executed (relative to the root directory of the content repository)

- Reference: unique name entered as a reference in the Power Apps

- Global Configuration ID: name of the Global Configuration Setup

- Owner: used to control permissions

Global Configuration 

In the global configuration, the Base URL for the Workplace is configured, along with the Authentication Type (Basic or OAuth). Choosing Basic requires a username and password. Choosing OAuth requires entering the OAuth AppId and OAuth Secret.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

The name is entered in the iFrame configuration under Global Config ID. The Description can be freely chosen and serves to describe the global configuration.

3.1.3. Variables 

![Ein Bild, das Text, Reihe, Zahl, Screenshot enthält.  Automatisch generierte Beschreibung](data:image/png;base64,)Variables are used to pre-configure additional information to be transmitted to the process when it starts. For example, the path to a specific Doxee Template.

Any number of variables can be defined and transmitted. It is important that these are actually read in at the start element of the Doxee process.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

3.1.4. Queries 

The Queries tab displays all queries that are queried at the start of the process. The linking of the query to the iFrame happens directly from the query. From the menu window (shown below), queries can be activated, deactivated, edited, or deleted. The dialog for creating a new query can also be directly accessed via "+ New Query".

![A screenshot of a phone  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

In Subchapter 3.1.4.1. we will explain, how to create a query.

3.1.4.1. Creating a Query 

To create a query, there are several mandatory fields to set. It should be noted that the query defines which iFrame configuration it is to be used in.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

- Name: unique name for the query (freely selectable)

- Entity: the object from which the data should be retrieved

- iFrame Config ID: the name of the iFrame configurations in which this query should be active

- Owner: used to control permissions

In the next tab "Filter", the columns from which the data should be retrieved are selected.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

Furthermore, filters can be defined to influence the result of the query.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

All settings can be checked below with the "View Records" button. Here, the result of the query is displayed live.

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

Once the Entity is set, the columns selected, and (optionally) filters set, the query can be saved ("Save"). This also creates the “Fetch XML”. It provides the XML structure that defines the dynamic data in the Doxee Template, which will then be replaced with the data from Microsoft Dynamics at runtime in the process.

![A close-up of a computer code  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

3.1.4.2. Example Data 

To create an example XML, this can be generated for each respective query under Sample Data:

![A screenshot of a computer  Description automatically generated](data:image/png;base64,)

Another window opens, displaying the example XML. This can be copied to the clipboard with the "Copy to Clipboard" button and pasted into an editor, for example, where it can then be saved as XML.

![Ein Bild, das Text, Screenshot, Software, Display enthält.  Automatisch generierte Beschreibung](data:image/png;base64,)

3.1.4.3. Linked Tables 

![Ein Bild, das Text, Screenshot, Reihe enthält.  Automatisch generierte Beschreibung](data:image/png;base64,)

Linked tables allow adding parent and child objects to the current query (join). With the help of these, for example, Account information and/or orders can also be read out in a query when dealing with the Contact object.

![Ein Bild, das Text, Screenshot, Zahl, Reihe enthält.  Automatisch generierte Beschreibung](data:image/png;base64,)

- In the Lookup field, the data field is selected that connects the two tables (foreign keys).

- To Table defines to which other object it wants to connect.

- The data fields are selected in the Columns.

- With the help of Alias, a temporary name can be assigned.

3.1.4.4. Query Parameters 

Any number of query parameters can be defined for each query. These primarily serve to define a variable, which will then be filled at runtime with the current data of the object.

For example, an ID of the object with the option dynamic will be filled with the ID of the object from which the process was started when the process is started.
